      "title": "Orthogonal circles and angle between tangents",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Angle of Intersection of Two Circles&nbsp;</strong></h3><h3><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"333\" height=\"220\">&nbsp;</h3><p>The angle between two circles is the angle between their tangents at their point of intersection.</p><p>Let $\\text{P}$ be a point of intersection of the two circles. Let PT and $\\text{P}{{\\text{T}}^{\\text{ }\\!\\!'\\!\\!\\text{ }}}$ be the tangents to the two circles at $\\text{P}$. Then the angle of intersection of the two circles at $\\text{P}$ is the $\\angle \\text{TP}{{\\text{T}}^{\\text{ }\\!\\!'\\!\\!\\text{ }}}$ or $\\pi -\\angle \\text{TP}{{\\text{T}}^{\\text{ }\\!\\!'\\!\\!\\text{ }}}$ If $\\text{A}$ and $\\text{B}$ be the centers of the two circles then $\\text{PA}\\bot \\text{PT}$ and $\\text{PB}\\bot \\text{{P}'}\\therefore \\angle \\text{TP}{{\\text{T}}^{\\text{ }\\!\\!'\\!\\!\\text{ }}}=\\angle \\text{APB}$ or $\\pi -\\angle \\text{APB}$.</p><p><strong>Orthogonal Circles</strong></p><p>Two circles are said to be intersect orthogonally when the tangents at their points of intersection are at right angles.</p><p>If the two circles intersect at $\\text{P}$, the radii, ${{\\text{O}}_{1}}\\text{P}$ and ${{\\text{O}}_{2}}\\text{P}$, which are perpendicular to the tangents at $\\text{P}$, must also be at right angles.</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"309\" height=\"225\">&nbsp;</p><p>Hence, ${{\\text{O}}_{1}}\\text{O}_{2}^{2}={{\\text{O}}_{1}}{{\\text{P}}^{2}}+{{\\text{O}}_{2}}{{\\text{P}}^{2}}$</p><p>i.e., the square of the distance between the centers must be equal to the sum of the squares of the radii.</p><p>Also, the tangent from ${{\\text{O}}_{2}}$ to the other circle is equal to the radius ${{\\text{a}}^{2}}$, i.e., if two circles be orthogonal the length of the tangent drawn from the Centre of one circle to the second circle is equal to the radius of the first.</p><p>Either of these two conditions will determine whether the circles are orthogonal.</p><p>The Centre’s of the circles,</p><p>${{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}+2gx+2fy+c=0\\text{ and }{{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}+2{g}'x+2{f}'y+{c}'=0$</p><p>are the points $\\left( -\\text{g},-\\text{f} \\right)$ and $\\left( -\\text{{g}'},-\\text{{f}'} \\right)$; also, the squares of their radii are</p><p>${{\\text{g}}^{2}}+{{\\text{f}}^{2}}-\\text{c }\\text{ and }{{\\text{g}}^{'2}}+{{\\text{f}}^{'2}}-\\text{{c}'}\\text{. }$</p><p>They therefore, cut orthogonally if</p><p>${{\\left( -\\text{g}+\\text{{g}'} \\right)}^{2}}+{{\\left( -\\text{f}+\\text{{f}'} \\right)}^{2}}={{\\text{g}}^{2}}+{{\\text{f}}^{2}}-\\text{c}+{{\\text{g}}^{'2}}+{{\\text{f}}^{'2}}-\\text{{c}'}$</p><p>i.e., if</p><p>$2\\text{g}{{\\text{g}}^{'}}+2\\text{f}{{\\text{f}}^{'}}=\\text{c}+\\text{{c}'}$</p>",
